  <Fragment slot="feature-comparisons">
    <h2 id="taste">Taste and cup texture</h2>
    <p>
      Let’s start with what you actually taste. AeroPress usually gives a cup with more clarity. By clarity, I mean you
      can pick out flavors more easily — citrus notes feel sharper, chocolate notes feel cleaner, and the finish is less
      muddy.
    </p>
    <p>
      French Press does the opposite on purpose. It lets more coffee oils and very fine particles through the filter, so
      the cup feels fuller and heavier. Imagine the difference between skim milk and whole milk. Same drink, totally
      different mouthfeel.
    </p>
    <p>
      One little gotcha: French Press shows you every flaw. Grind a bit too fine and you get sludge. Let it sit too long
      and it can tip bitter fast. AeroPress hides more of that with a paper filter, but you will buy filters (or use a
      metal one).
    </p>
    <p>
      Neither one is objectively better. If you want something bright and clean, AeroPress has the edge. If you want a
      cup that feels thicker and bolder, French Press is hard to beat for the price.
    </p>

    <h3>How grind size changes the result</h3>
    <p>
      Grind size matters for both brewers, but French Press punishes bad grind quality more. If your grounds are uneven,
      French Press can taste harsh and leave gritty sludge in the bottom of your mug. AeroPress is more forgiving because
      the paper filter catches more fines.
    </p>
    <p>
      If your grinder struggles with consistency, check our
      <a href="/posts/best-coffee-grinder-for-french-press.html">best coffee grinder for French Press</a> guide. If you
      want cleaner cups across manual brewing methods, our
      <a href="/posts/best-coffee-grinder-for-pour-over.html">best coffee grinder for pour-over</a> guide is also worth a
      look.
    </p>

    <h2 id="speed-and-cleanup">Speed, cleanup, and daily friction</h2>
    <p>
      Morning coffee is not just flavor. It is also friction. Tiny annoying steps add up when you are tired. AeroPress
      wins this part for most people. Brew, press, pop the puck into the bin, quick rinse, done.
    </p>
    <p>
      French Press is not hard, but it is messier. You have wet grounds stuck in a beaker, a mesh filter to rinse, and
      sometimes stubborn sludge around the plunger screen. If that sounds small, it does not feel small at 6:45 AM.
    </p>
    <p>Here is a simple workflow view so you can picture your day before you buy.</p>

    <HeroSteps
      title="Daily Brew Workflow: AeroPress vs French Press"
      subtitle="Where each method saves or costs you time"
      steps={[
        { label: 'Prep', icon: 'list', actions: ['Heat water', 'Grind beans', 'Set brewer and mug'], time: '~3 min both' },
        {
          label: 'Brew',
          icon: 'timer',
          actions: ['AeroPress: shorter steep and press', 'French Press: longer steep then plunge', 'Both simple once dialed in'],
          time: '~2 min vs ~4 min',
        },
        {
          label: 'Cleanup',
          icon: 'check',
          actions: ['AeroPress: eject puck + rinse', 'French Press: discard wet grounds', 'Rinse mesh and beaker well'],
          time: '~30 sec vs ~2–3 min',
        },
      ]}
      outcome="If fast, low-mess mornings matter to you, AeroPress usually feels easier to live with"
    />

    <h3>Portability and travel reality</h3>
    <p>
      AeroPress is one of the best travel brewers ever made. It is compact, durable, and can work in hotel rooms,
      offices, and campsites with almost no fuss. French Press can travel too, but glass models are awkward and stainless
      options are bulkier than most people expect.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you brew away from home even once or twice a month, portability alone can be the deciding factor. That is why
      so many people call AeroPress their “weekday and travel” brewer even when they still own a French Press for
      weekends.
    </p>

    <h2 id="alternatives">What about pour-over and Moka pot?</h2>
    <p>
      When people ask for the best AeroPress alternative, they are often really asking: “What else makes great coffee
      without espresso-level cost?” In that case, French Press is the obvious first answer. But pour-over and Moka pot
      deserve a quick look too.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Pour-over</strong> is great if you love clarity and control. It can taste cleaner than both AeroPress and
      French Press, but it asks more from your pouring technique and kettle control. If you enjoy a small daily ritual,
      it is fantastic. If you want speed and consistency while sleepy, it can feel fussy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Moka pot</strong> is the bold option. It does not make true espresso, but it makes a concentrated, punchy
      cup that works well with milk drinks. Think of it as the “stovetop intensity” path. It is a better AeroPress
      alternative for people chasing stronger body, not cleaner nuance.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you are still dialing in consistency, start with our
      <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a>. Ratios sound nerdy, but they are
      just a repeatable recipe. Keep your ratio steady and your brewer comparisons get way easier.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="buyer-profiles">
    <h2 id="buy-this-if">Buy this if... skip this if...</h2>

    <h3>Choose AeroPress if this sounds like you</h3>
    <p>
      You brew one cup at a time. You want a clean, smooth cup with low bitterness. You value fast cleanup and compact
      gear. You travel or carry coffee gear to work. You like a brewer that is forgiving when your grind or timing is not
      perfect.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Skip AeroPress</strong> if you regularly brew for two or three people at once, or if you strongly prefer a
      thick, oil-rich cup texture every day.
    </p>

    <h3>Choose French Press if this sounds like you</h3>
    <p>
      You love rich body and deeper mouthfeel. You often brew multiple cups in one batch. You do not mind a little
      sediment in the cup. You enjoy a slower, calmer brew routine and cleanup does not bother you.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Skip French Press</strong> if you hate messy cleanup, want maximum portability, or get annoyed by even a
      little grit in your coffee.
    </p>

    <h3>My practical take</h3>
    <p>
      If I had to recommend one brewer for most people buying today, I would still hand them an AeroPress first. It is
      easier to live with, easier to clean, and easier to make consistently good coffee with. But if your dream cup is
      thick, cozy, and full-bodied, French Press is the better emotional fit. Pick based on your mornings, not on
      internet arguments.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

