  <Fragment slot="extra-sections">
    <section>
      <h2>How to get better cups no matter which brewer you pick</h2>
      <p>
        You can absolutely make good coffee with either brewer on day one. But if you want that “wow, this is way
        better” jump, focus on three things first: fresh beans, consistent grind, and repeatable ratios.
      </p>
      <p>
        Fresh beans are obvious, but grind consistency is where most home setups fall apart. A cheap blade grinder chops
        beans into random chunks and dust. That gives you both under-extracted and over-extracted flavors in the same
        cup. Translation: sour plus bitter at the same time. Not fun.
      </p>
      <p>
        A burr grinder crushes beans to a more even size, so water pulls flavor out more evenly. You do not need a luxury
        grinder to feel the difference. Even a decent entry-level burr grinder can make French Press less muddy and make
        AeroPress recipes easier to dial in.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ratios are your safety net. A ratio is just coffee-to-water balance. If one cup tastes too strong, use more water
        next time. If it tastes thin, use a little more coffee. Keep notes for a week and you will find your sweet spot
        faster than changing everything at once.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Common mistakes that make both methods taste worse</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Mistake one: changing too many things at once.</strong> If you adjust grind, dose, water temp, and brew
        time in one go, you will not know what fixed or broke the cup. Change one thing. Keep the rest stable.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Mistake two: using water that is way too hot.</strong> Boiling water straight on delicate beans can push
        bitterness. Let water sit briefly after boiling before brewing. Tiny habit, big improvement.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Mistake three: ignoring cleanup quality.</strong> Old oils in filters, plungers, or mesh screens can make
        fresh coffee taste stale. A quick rinse is not always enough. Give your gear a deeper clean regularly so your cup
        keeps tasting like coffee, not yesterday’s residue.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you want a full cleanup routine, this page is a good companion:
        <a href="/posts/how-to-clean-burr-coffee-grinder.html">How to Clean a Burr Coffee Grinder</a>. Cleaner gear,
        cleaner flavor.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Final call: which one should you buy today?</h2>
      <p>
        If you are still undecided, here is the blunt version. Buy AeroPress if you care about speed, portability, and
        low-mess mornings. Buy French Press if you care about rich body and brewing more than one cup in one shot. That
        is the real fork in the road.
      </p>
      <p>
        For most people moving from basic drip or pods, AeroPress feels easier to succeed with right away. For people who
        want a heavier, fuller cup and do not mind cleanup, French Press stays deeply satisfying long term.
      </p>
      <p>
        So yes, French Press is often the best AeroPress alternative. But if you want the least friction and the most
        consistent weekday routine, AeroPress still deserves the top spot for daily use.
      </p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</VsComparison>
